[3] Amoebic dysentery - American Samoa
Date: Wed 14 May 2014
Source: Radio New Zealand International [edited]
http://www.radionz.co.nz/international/pacific-news/244374/amoebic-dysentery-outbreak-in-american-samoa


Health officials in American Samoa are warning the public about an amoebic dysentery outbreak which has so far affected 26 people, half of which have been admitted to the LBJ hospital. A Pacific Island Health Officers' Association Epidemiologist, Mark Duran, says the department of health is leading an investigation into the source of the parasite.

Dr Duran says amoebic dysentery is spread through contamination of human waste. "It especially attacks the intestines and invades its way into the wall of the intestines; it causes abdominal pain, it causes bloody diarrhea, fever." Dr Duran says in serious cases the parasite can travel through the body and cause abscesses especially in the liver.

